english:
  title: On the Azalea Flower
  author: Jok Joyeong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    What year was this flower planted within the palace walls?
    Nature's craftsman lavished every cutting and carving on it.
    The delicate leaves need no further adorning in green—
    yet the tender blooms already glow with vibrant crimson.

    How many times has rain beaded like pearls on the branches?
    A breeze sweeps one thread of fragrance beyond the pavilion.
    When the palace maidens come to pluck these flowers,
    dew mingles with their rosy powder, staining fingertips with spring.
  footnotes:
    - Azaleas (척촉화) were prized ornamental flowers in East Asian courts, symbolic of spring and feminine beauty.
    - The poem plays on the tension between natural beauty and courtly artifice, suggesting how even cultivated flowers retain their wild essence.
